				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/anaxagoras" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1019930); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1019930&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610182999" alt="Anaxagoras" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1019930)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/anaxagoras" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1019930); return false;" >Anaxagoras</a></span> <span class="odate time_1310949846 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">18 Jul 2011 00:44</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1203924">
									

<p>The article is good. I like the creature, though I'm not sure if arthropods as a group are that big on mucus. It's certainly understandable why it's an SCP; the unusual response of children is very interesting.</p>
<p>But Bland is right: It is, unmistakably, an angler fish of some sort. There's no particular reason for it to be so, and every reason for it to be otherwise. Arthropods simply don't have physiology even remotely like that, and you devote a whole paragraph to explaining why it does, which still doesn't satisfy.<br />
I understand why you use a picture of an angler fish. Mr. Sillybug (incidentally, I'd make that the name of the article on the main list) should look horrific, and angler fish do certainly look horrific. But it seems like it would be pretty easy to get an actual close-up of the head of some not terribly recognizable arthropod and just use that as the image, and cull that pointless paragraph and remedy some of the complaints.</p>

